## Appendix: substrate mapping

The enforcement substrate uses fixed git conventions. This mapping
is operational — it explains what the agent sees in git output.
It is not part of the normal working language.

| This project says | Git shows | Branch prefix |
|---|---|---|
| {{nouns.floor}} | submodule gitlinks, pinned commits | `past/` |
| {{nouns.claim}} | staged and working changes | (the `now` branch itself) |
| {{nouns.experiment}} | separate branches with declared ties | `future/` |
| enforcement rules | manifest and hook source | `meta` |

When git output shows `future/parser-spike`, read that as
"a {{nouns.experiment}} named parser-spike." When it shows
`past/rca0`, read that as "a {{nouns.floor}} line named rca0."

The `.gitmodules` file declares each entry's role (`role = past`,
`role = future`) and, for explorations, which {{nouns.floor}} line
the exploration belongs to (`ancestor-constraint = <name>`). The
enforcement hooks read these declarations. The agent does not
edit them directly — the acts handle that.
